ce:section.ce:para:
While there exists a comprehensive ANN model for predicting the thermal conductivity of nanofluids [24], the thermal conductivity of metals, and metal oxides based nanofluids [21,25] and thermal conductivity of ethylene glycol-based hybrid nanofluids [26], no study is yet to propose a comprehensive model for predicting the thermal conductivity of hybrid nanofluids using various base fluids. The study presents a novel comprehensive artificial neural network-based model for predicting the thermal conductivity of different hybrid nanofluids. The network uses seven different input variables namely, volume concentration, temperature, the acentric factor of the base fluid, nanoparticle bulk density, mixture ratio of particles, the thermal conductivity, and size of nanoparticles. 715 experimental data points from various studies using different hybrid nanoparticles are used in developing a Multi-Layer Perceptron artificial neural network (MLP-ANN) and Support Vector Regression (SVR) models. The performance validation of the models is carried out using the mean square error (MSE) and the coefficient of determination (R

                        2
                     ). Finally, a universal formula using MLP-ANN for predicting the thermal conductivity of hybrid nanofluids is presented.
